  "text": "The greatest differences in the relative importance between motives emerged between women and men. Women demonstrated significantly higher means than men on 10 out of 15 TEMS scales. The difference was especially pronounced for affect regulation and body weight control reasons. Also, Steptoe and colleagues (1995) reported consistent gender differences with women having higher values on all food choice motives except Sensory Appeal and Familiarity. That women rated nearly every eating motivation as more frequently influencing eating behavior than men could be due to women being more preoccupied with food in general [CITATION_1] .",
